HOME NETWORK SECURITY ASSESSMENT REPORT
Analyst: Diana Magana
Date: February 12, 2026
Classification: Personal/Educational
Project Type: Portfolio Security Assessment

EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
I conducted a security assessment on my home network environment to identify vulnerabilities and security misconfigurations. The assessment utilized industry-standard network reconnaissance tools and methodologies to evaluate the security posture of network infrastructure and connected devices.

Key Findings:

1 Medium-severity finding identified requiring remediation
Network perimeter security confirmed adequate (WPA2/WPA3 encryption)
No critical or high-severity vulnerabilities discovered
No unauthorized devices detected on network

Overall Security Posture: GOOD with one medium-risk misconfiguration requiring attention
Primary Finding: Expired SSL/TLS certificate on network gateway creates potential man-in-the-middle vulnerability and represents configuration drift requiring remediation through proper access channels.
Operational Impact: This assessment demonstrates real-world security operations where vulnerability identification, risk assessment, and remediation planning must account for access constraints and operational considerations. Professional security practice requires not just technical scanning capabilities but also risk management and cross-functional coordination skills.

ASSESSMENT SCOPE
Network Range: 192.168.1.0/24 (254 possible hosts)
Assessment Duration: 8 hours over two weekends
Assessment Type: Internal network security audit
Environment: Home network, Qatar
In-Scope:

Network gateway/router (192.168.1.1)
All connected devices on primary network
Network services and exposed ports
Service versions and configurations
SSL/TLS certificate validity

Out-of-Scope:

Wireless security penetration testing
Application-layer vulnerability testing
Endpoint security assessment
Social engineering testing
Physical security assessment


METHODOLOGY
Tools Used
Primary Tool:

Nmap 7.95 (Network Mapper)

Service version detection (-sV)
Default script scanning (-sC)
SSL certificate validation scripts
Output formatting (-oN)



Secondary Tools:

Native OS networking commands (ipconfig)
Browser-based configuration interface access attempts
Manual device identification

Assessment Approach
Phase 1: Network Discovery (2 hours)

I Identified network addressing scheme
Performed host discovery scan
Enumerated active devices
Documented network topology

Phase 2: Service Enumeration (2 hours)

Port scanning of all discovered hosts
Service version detection
Operating system fingerprinting
Protocol identification

Phase 3: Vulnerability Analysis (2 hours)

SSL/TLS certificate validation
Default credential checking
Outdated service identification
Configuration review

Phase 4: Documentation & Reporting (2 hours)

Finding classification
Risk assessment
Remediation planning
Report generation


