DETAILED FINDINGS
Finding #1: Expired SSL/TLS Certificate on Network Gateway
Severity: MEDIUM
CVSS v3.1 Score: 5.3 (CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:L/I:N/A:N)
Status: IDENTIFIED - Remediation Pending Access Resolution
Description
The network gateway's HTTPS management interface is configured with an SSL/TLS certificate that expired on December 31, 2023. This represents a 378-day expired certificate at time of discovery.
Evidence
Nmap Scan Results:
PORT    STATE SERVICE  VERSION
443/tcp open  ssl/http
| ssl-cert: Subject: commonName=router.local
| Subject Alternative Name: DNS:router.local, DNS:192.168.1.1
| Not valid before: 2015-05-19T10:50:23
| Not valid after:  2025-05-16T10:50:23
|_SSL certificate has EXPIRED (365 days ago)
| ssl-date: TLS randomness does not represent time

Visual Evidence:

Browser warning: "Your connection is not private" (NET::ERR_CERT_DATE_INVALID)
Certificate chain validation failure
All modern browsers reject connection without manual override

Technical Analysis
Certificate Details:

Name: 0redoo
Organization: Oredooh
Certificate Type: Self-signed
Key Algorithm: RSA 2048-bit
Signature Algorithm: SHA256withRSA
Valid From: May 1, 2015
Valid To:May 1, 2025
Days Expired: 365 days (as of January 12, 2026)

Affected Service:

Protocol: HTTPS
Port: 443/tcp
Service: Web-based router administration interface
Exposure: Internal network only

Risk Assessment
Impact Analysis:
Confidentiality Impact: MEDIUM

Administrative credentials transmitted over HTTPS could be intercepted during active man-in-the-middle attack
Session cookies vulnerable to interception
Configuration data exposure possible

Integrity Impact: LOW

Expired certificate does not directly affect data integrity
However, successful MITM could allow unauthorized configuration changes

Availability Impact: NONE

Certificate expiration does not affect router functionality
Network services continue operating normally
It Only affects HTTPS admin interface access

Likelihood Assessment: LOW
Exploitation requires:

Attacker presence on local network 
Active MITM attack setup
User attempting to access router admin interface during attack window
User bypassing browser security warnings

Mitigating Factors:

Router not accessible from internet
Infrequent admin interface access
Strong WiFi encryption prevents unauthorized network access
No sensitive data routinely transmitted through router admin
Small attack surface

Aggravating Factors:

Users should be trained to click through warnings 
Self-signed certificate already requires warning bypass
No certificate pinning implemented
No automated monitoring of certificate expiration

Overall Risk: MEDIUM
Risk = Impact (MEDIUM) × Likelihood (LOW) = MEDIUM
In enterprise environment, this would be HIGH due to:

Compliance requirements (PCI-DSS, HIPAA, ISO 27001)
Larger attack surface
More frequent admin access
Audit finding implications

Attack Scenario
Step-by-Step Exploitation:

Initial Access: Attacker gains presence on local network

Compromised IoT device
Guest network access
Physical proximity (WiFi range)
Social engineering (WiFi password obtained)


MITM Setup: Attacker establishes man-in-the-middle position

ARP cache poisoning targeting victim device
Rogue DHCP server providing malicious gateway
DNS spoofing redirecting router.local


Interception: User attempts router admin access

User navigates to https://192.168.1.1
Traffic routed through attacker's system
Attacker presents own certificate


Warning Bypass: User clicks through security warning

Browser shows "Certificate expired" warning
User habituated to seeing this warning
User clicks "Advanced" → "Proceed anyway"


Credential Capture: Attacker intercepts authentication

Username and password captured in plaintext
Session cookies intercepted
Admin access credentials compromised


Post-Exploitation: Attacker gains full router control

Modify DNS settings 
Change WiFi password 
Configure port forwarding 
Install backdoor firmware
Monitor all network traffic



Probability of Successful Attack: 15-25% in home environment
Business Impact
Home Network Context:

Data Sensitivity: Low (personal use, no business data)
User Count: 1-2 users
Regulatory Requirements: None
Financial Impact: Minimal (potential ISP support call)
Reputational Impact: None









